etymologies: Middle English; earliest use found in Exchequer Accounts. From Anglo-Norman plancher, planchier, plauncher, plauncheour floor, and Old French, Middle French plancher, planchier planking, flooring, floor of a house, ceiling, roof, the floor of a cavity in the body from planche + -er, -ier

definitions: A floor of planks or boards (now English regional (East Anglian)). Formerly also: †a platform of planks (obsolete).
A wooden plank, a board; (also, collectively) planking, boarding.
In France: the minimum amount of currency in Treasury bills which banks are obliged to hold.
